# Cursor Rules for React + MUI Project

## Project Context
- Framework: React 18+
- Language: TypeScript (strict mode)
- Build Tool: Vite
- UI Library: Material UI (MUI) v6
- Routing: React Router v6
- State Management: Context API (default unless specified)
- Styling: MUI `sx` prop + `styled()` — Tailwind is NOT used in this project

---

##  UI Library Rules

### MUI is the ONLY UI library
- Do NOT use Tailwind, Chakra, Ant Design, or any other UI/CSS library
- Do NOT write plain CSS files unless absolutely unavoidable (e.g., third-party widget reset)
- If a UI element exists in MUI, use it — do NOT recreate it manually

### Imports
- Always import from `@mui/material` or `@mui/icons-material`
- Use MUI v6 Grid2 for layouts: import from `@mui/material/Grid2`
- Avoid deep imports unless the component is not re-exported from the top level
- ✅ `import { Button } from '@mui/material'`
- ❌ `import Button from '@mui/material/Button'` (only if needed for tree-shaking in edge cases)

### Styling Priority (in order)
1. MUI `sx` prop (preferred for one-off styles)
2. `styled()` API (preferred for reusable styled variants)
3. Theme overrides via `components` key in `createTheme`
4. Inline style objects (only for truly dynamic values like JS-computed pixel values)

### Theme
- ALL color, spacing, typography, and breakpoint values must come from the MUI theme
- Never hardcode hex colors, font sizes, or spacing values — use `theme.palette.*`, `theme.spacing()`, `theme.typography.*`
- ThemeProvider must wrap the app at the root level
- Custom theme lives in `src/theme/index.ts`
- Define custom palette, typography scale, shape, and component overrides there

### MUI Component Usage
Prefer these MUI components for common patterns:

| Need | Use |
|---|---|
| Layout | `Box`, `Container`, `Stack`, `Grid2` |
| Text input | `TextField` (includes label + error state) |
| Select | `Select` + `MenuItem` inside `FormControl` |
| Buttons | `Button`, `IconButton`, `LoadingButton` (from `@mui/lab`) |
| Feedback | `Snackbar` + `Alert`, `CircularProgress`, `Skeleton` |
| Navigation | `AppBar`, `Drawer`, `Tabs`, `Breadcrumbs` |
| Data display | `Table`, `List`, `Chip`, `Avatar` |
| Overlay | `Dialog`, `Tooltip`, `Popover` |

### Icons
- Use `@mui/icons-material` for standard icons
- Use custom SVGs only when no MUI icon fits — wrap in `SvgIcon` for consistency
- Always pass `fontSize` and `color` as props, not via CSS

---

## Project Structure
src/
components/     # Reusable UI components (no page-specific logic)
pages/          # Route-level components (thin — delegate to components/hooks)
hooks/          # Custom React hooks
services/       # API calls and external integrations
utils/          # Pure helper functions (no React)
types/          # TypeScript types and interfaces
theme/          # MUI theme config (index.ts + any sub-files)
context/        # React Context definitions and providers
Rules:
- Do NOT mix responsibilities across folders
- `pages/` components should be thin — business logic goes into hooks, UI into components
- `services/` functions must be pure async functions with no React dependencies
- `context/` contains Provider + hook (e.g., `useAuth`) — not raw `useContext` calls in components

---

## TypeScript Rules
- Strict mode must be enabled in `tsconfig.json`
- NEVER use `any` — use `unknown` and narrow, or define proper types
- Always type component props explicitly with an interface
- Use `React.FC` sparingly — prefer explicit return type annotations
- Co-locate types with the component if they're component-specific; move to `src/types/` if shared
- Use discriminated unions for state that has multiple modes (loading/error/success)

```ts
// ✅ Good
interface UserCardProps {
  user: User;
  onSelect: (id: string) => void;
}

// ❌ Bad
const UserCard = ({ user, onSelect }: any) => { ... }
```

---

## React Rules
- Functional components ONLY — no class components
- Use hooks — never replicate hook behavior inline
- Destructure props in the function signature
- Avoid `useEffect` for derived state — compute it inline or with `useMemo`
- Use `useEffect` only for true side effects (subscriptions, DOM manipulation, syncing external systems)
- Use `useCallback` only when passing callbacks to memoized children or as `useEffect` deps — not by default
- Use `useMemo` only for genuinely expensive computations — not as a default

---

## Async & Data Fetching
- Use `async/await` — no `.then()` chains
- All API calls live in `src/services/`
- Handle three states explicitly: loading, error, success — use `Skeleton` or `CircularProgress` for loading, `Alert` for errors
- Use early returns to handle error/loading before the happy path

```ts
// ✅ Good pattern
if (loading) return <Skeleton />;
if (error) return <Alert severity="error">{error.message}</Alert>;
return <DataView data={data} />;
```

---

## Forms
- Use `react-hook-form` for all forms unless the form has a single field
- Pair with MUI `TextField` via the `Controller` component
- Never manage form field state manually with `useState` arrays
- Always define a Zod schema for validation — use `@hookform/resolvers/zod`
- ASK before introducing a different form library

---

## Code Style
- Arrow functions for components and utilities
- `const` over `let`; never `var`
- Single quotes
- Semicolons required
- 2-space indentation
- Meaningful, intention-revealing variable names
- Early returns to reduce nesting

---

## Accessibility
- All interactive elements must be keyboard-accessible (MUI handles most of this by default)
- Always provide `aria-label` on `IconButton` — it has no visible text
- Use semantic HTML inside MUI components (`component` prop: e.g., `<Box component="nav">`)
- Images need `alt` text; decorative images get `alt=""`
- Form fields must always have an associated label (use MUI `TextField` which handles this)

---

## Component Design
- Keep components focused on a single responsibility
- Prefer composition over configuration (multiple small components over one giant one with many props)
- Split a component when it exceeds ~200 lines OR when it handles more than one concern
- Extract reusable logic into custom hooks in `src/hooks/`
- Do NOT duplicate logic — if you write it twice, extract it

---

## Refactoring Rules
- Improve readability without changing behavior
- Break large components by responsibility, not by arbitrary line count
- Extract logic into hooks when it's reusable or when it clutters the JSX
- After refactoring, verify the component renders identically

---

## AI Behavior Rules
- ALWAYS explain your approach BEFORE writing code
- NEVER modify files unrelated to the task
- ALWAYS follow existing patterns found in the codebase (patterns override these rules)
- ASK before:
  - Adding any new npm dependency
  - Introducing global state or a new Context
  - Restructuring folders or renaming files
  - Using a non-MUI styling solution
  - Adding a new form library or data-fetching abstraction
- Prefer simple solutions — if a simpler approach exists, suggest it
- When generating UI, default to MUI components
- If unsure whether a pattern exists in the codebase, ask rather than guess

---

## Prompt Interpretation
| User says | AI does |
|---|---|
| "create component" | Typed interface + MUI components + clean JSX + co-located types |
| "fix bug" | Minimal change, preserve surrounding logic, explain root cause |
| "refactor" | Improve structure/readability, no behavior change, explain what changed and why |
| "add form" | `react-hook-form` + Zod + MUI `Controller` pattern |
| "add page" | Thin page component + new route entry + delegate logic to hooks |

---

## Hard Constraints (never violate)
- No class components
- No `any` in TypeScript
- No new libraries without approval
- No hardcoded colors, spacing, or font sizes (use theme tokens)
- No recreating MUI components from scratch
- No over-engineering (YAGNI)
- No logic duplication

---

## Priority Order
1. Existing codebase patterns
2. These rules
3. General React/TypeScript best practices